dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#GeneralDescription
dataObjects.title: Biology
dataObjects.description: Occurs in large upland rivers.  Common in areas with rocky bottoms and irregular depths (Ref. 12693).  Apparently does not migrate but reproduces locally and enters the flooded forest during high water in July-October (Ref. 38441).  Feeds on insects, prawns, fish (Ref. 33813) and crabs (Ref. 38441).  Marketed fresh (Ref. 12693).  Maximum weight reported for an individual caught in Mae Klong River, Thailand, reached 86 kg (J-F. Helias, pers.comm., 07/2002; see photo Hewyc_u0.jpg).

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Distribution
dataObjects.description: Southeastern Asia, Mekong River basin: Cambodia, Cambodia, China and Thailand.

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Distribution
dataObjects.description: Asia:  Mekong basin (Ref. 27732).  Reported from Chao Phraya, Maeklong and Peninsular Thailand river systems (Ref. 26336).

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#DiagnosticDescription
dataObjects.description: Bright red caudal fin in specimens bigger than about 15 cm SL; whitish in smaller ones (Ref. 27732).  Adipose fin long (length of adipose-fin base 18.7-25.7% SL), with a gently-sloping anterior margin; dorsal spine poorly ossified and short (7.5-11.4% SL) without serrations on posterior edge; length of dorsal-fin base 16.3-18.3% SL; maxillary barbels reaching to at least middle of adipose fin base (230.1-297.0% HL) (Ref. 38441).  Head flat rather than conical; a short occipital process not close to basal bone of dorsal fin; no stripes on body (Ref. 12693).

dataObjects.subject: http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/SPMInfoItems#Migration
dataObjects.description: Potamodromous. Migrating within streams, migratory in rivers, e.g. Saliminus, Moxostoma, Labeo.  Migrations should be cyclical and predictable and cover more than 100 km.

dataObjects.title: File:Hemibagrus wyckioides Mae Chaem December 2013.jpg
dataObjects.description: English: 1=Pla kot khang (Thai script: ปลากดคัง) (sometimes also called pla khang or just pla kot for short) is a type of catfish used in Thai cuisine for tom yam or, shortly blanched, to be eaten with a nam chim. The school of fish in this image were photographed swimming in the Mae Chaem River beneath the bridge in the town of Mae Chaem near sunset. They were feeding off insects that were flying just above the water surface.
